Attribute `opmi_medicalConditionStatus` from [ext[OPMI_0000533|http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OPMI_0000533]]. This attribute describes the status or stage of a disease or health condition during the medical diagnostic process.

The following is the Chinese explanation for each of the optional values of this field:

# ''admissionDiagnosis'': admissionDiagnosis - The initial diagnosis made when the patient was admitted to the hospital.
# ''causeOfDeath'': cause of death - the disease or condition that caused the patient's death.
# ''conditionToBeDiagnosedByProcedure'': Disease or Condition to be Diagnosed by Procedure - A disease or condition that requires surgery or a specific medical procedure to confirm.
# ''confirmedDiagnosis'': Confirmed Diagnosis - A diagnosis that has been confirmed after examination and analysis.
# ''contributoryCauseOfDeath'': Secondary Cause of Death - A disease or condition that contributes to death, although it is not the direct cause of death.
# ''deathDiagnosis'': Death Diagnosis - A disease or condition determined after death.
# ''dischargeDiagnosis'': Discharge Diagnosis - A diagnosis made at the time the patient was discharged from the hospital.
# ''postoperativeDiagnosis'': Postoperative Diagnosis - A diagnosis made after surgery.
# ''preliminaryDiagnosis'': Preliminary Diagnosis - A provisional diagnosis made at the time of the first visit, which may need to be confirmed by further tests and analysis.
# ''preoperativeDiagnosis'': Preoperative Diagnosis - Diagnosis made before surgery.
# ''primaryDiagnosis'': Primary diagnosis - the patient's main health problem or disease.
# ''referralDiagnosis'': Referral Diagnosis - A diagnosis given when a patient is referred by another doctor or healthcare organization.
# ''resolvedCondition'': Resolved Condition - A pre-existing disease or condition that has now been resolved.
# ''secondaryDiagnosis'': Secondary Diagnosis - A health problem or disease other than the primary diagnosis.

These diagnostic statuses help doctors, nurses, and other healthcare professionals understand a patient's health condition so they can provide appropriate medical care and recommendations.

